Jan was often paired on tours with fellow Decca artist and singer-songwriter, [[Bill Anderson (singer)|Bill Anderson]]. The pair garnered positive audience reception when singing duets on tour, which prompted them to approach Owen Bradley about recording together. Bradley agreed to a "trial single" in 1965 called "I Know You're Married (But I Love You Still)".{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=252-53}} It was followed by 1967's "[[For Loving You]]", which topped the US country chart and made the top ten on the Canadian [[RPM (magazine)|country tracks]] chart.<ref name="RPM Country Songs">{{cite web|title=Search results for "Jan Howard" under Country Singles|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=2iqcjne94r17d52pg4oalqlm31&q1=Jan+Howard&q2=Country+Singles&interval=20|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130219183758/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=2iqcjne94r17d52pg4oalqlm31&q1=Jan+Howard&q2=Country+Singles&interval=20|url-status=dead|archive-date=19 February 2013|publisher=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=17 January 2013}}</ref> The duo's debut album of the [[For Loving You (album)|same name]] reached number six on the country albums chart in 1968.<ref name="Bill Anderson Country Albums">{{cite book |title=Joel Whitburn Presents Hot Country Albums: 1964-2007 |date=2008 |publisher=Record Research, Inc. |isbn=978-0898201734 |page=20}}</ref> Now a successful musical collaboration, Howard joined Anderson's roadshow and also became part of his syndicated television program called ''The Bill Anderson Show''.{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=250}} Because it was mostly filmed in [[Windsor, Ontario]], Jan traveled by commercial airlines to film tapings.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=311}} Working with Anderson provided Jan with a steady source of income{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=277}} following her divorce from Harlan Howard in the late 1960s.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=229}}

In 1968, Jan had three more top 40 US country solo singles including the number 16 "[[Count Your Blessings, Woman]]"<ref name="Ency">{{cite book |last1=Stambler |first1=Irwin |last2=Landon |first2=Grelun |title=Country Music: The Encyclopedia |date=2000 |publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]] |isbn=978-0312264871 |page=210-211}}</ref> and the number 15 "[[My Son (song)|My Son]]".<ref name="Allmusic Bio"/> The latter was inspired by a letter she wrote to her eldest son, Jimmy{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=229}} who was drafted into the [[United States Army|army]] to fight in the [[Vietnam War]].<ref name="Gazette">[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=gL9scSG3K_gC&dat=19681102&printsec=frontpage&hl=en "'My Son' Killed In Viet War"], ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'', November 2, 1968, p2</ref><ref>[http://www.vvmf.org/Wall-of-Faces/24318/JAMES-V-HOWARD Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund site]</ref> Despite Jan's reluctance, her middle son (Carter), Bill Anderson and Owen Bradley all encouraged her to record it.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=349-50}} After the song became commercially-successful, Jan received over 5,000 letters from soldiers and their families. "They said they felt like it was for them," she commented.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=229}} The song was later nominated for [[Best Female Country Vocal Performance]] at the [[Grammy Awards]].<ref name="Grammys"/> Before the end of 1968, Jimmy Howard was killed in battle, aged 21.<ref name="Gazette"/>

Despite her son's death, Jan continued touring, appearing on Anderson's show and recording.{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=250}} Her 1969 [[Jan Howard (1969 album)|eponymous LP]] reached the US country albums top 25<ref name="Country Albums"/> and included the US top 30 singles "[[I Still Believe in Love]]" and "[[When We Tried]]".<ref name="1960s Country Songs"/> It was followed by 1970 LP of [[American patriotic music|patriotic music]] called ''[[For God and Country (Jan Howard album)|For God and Country]]''<ref name="Ency"/> which was inspired by the death of her son.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=365-66}} The Anderson-Howard duet pairing continued simultaneously<ref name="Ency"/> and resulted in the three more top ten US and Canadian country singles through 1972: "[[If It's All the Same to You]]" (1970), "[[Someday We'll Be Together]]" (1970) and "[[Dis-Satisfied]]" (1972).<ref name="Top 40 Country Hits">{{cite book |last1=Whitburn |first1=Joel |title=The Billboard Book of Top 40 Country Hits |date=2006 |publisher=Billboard Books |isbn=978-0823082919 |page=164}}</ref> The singles were also issued on corresponding duet LP's that made the US country top 25: ''[[If It's All the Same to You (album)|If It's All the Same to You]]'' (1970) and ''[[Bill and Jan (Or Jan and Bill)]]'' (1972).<ref name="Bill Anderson Country Albums"/> Howard's solo releases made the US country songs top 40 twice more through 1970: "[[We Had All the Good Things Going]]" (1969) and "[[Rock Me Back to Little Rock]]" (1970).<ref name="Top 40 Country Hits"/> Both appeared on her 1970 top 40 LP, also titled ''[[Rock Me Back to Little Rock]]''.<ref name="Country Albums"/>

===1973–2020: New directions and slowing down===
Howard left Bill Anderson's road and television shows. "I wasn't mentally or physically able to keep up the pace doing the show full time," she later wrote.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=454}} Anderson replaced her with a newer artist named [[Mary Lou Turner]] and Howard was working by herself again. She had fewer concert dates than before and was working with pick-up bands who "would have made good electricians", according to Howard. Some nights, she performed with little to no instrumentation. During one booked engagement, she performed on the back of a flatbed truck. "Many nights I'd be so depressed and ashamed, I'd go back to the motel, cry and go to sleep," Howard wrote.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=454}} During this time, she began touring with [[Johnny Cash]] and [[June Carter Cash]] as part of their roadshow.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=229}} "It'll do you good," the Cashes said to her. Howard toured with the show nationally and internationally. This included performances in [[Hawaii]] and [[Australia]].{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=462}} Not only touring together, Howard also joined Cash in the recording studio. She sang background vocals on some of his biggest hits. This included singing the line, "Mama sang tenor", on his 1969 hit "[[Daddy Sang Bass]]". She also was a background vocalist on Cash's 1963 hit "[[Ring of Fire (song)|Ring of Fire]]".<ref name="Digital Journal Interview">{{cite web |last1=Papadatos |first1=Markos |title=Interview with Jan Howard: Classiest Lady in Country Music |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/a-and-e/music/interview-with-jan-howard-classiest-lady-in-country-music/article/377906 |website=Digital Journal |access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>
[[File:Jan Singing on the Opry in Brown Jacket.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Howard on stage at the Opry, 2000s]]

Howard also returned to the recording studio. During this period, she was a neighbor of Nashville producer, [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]],{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=467}} who produced her next studio album. Titled ''Sincerely, Jan Howard'', it was issued on [[GRT Records]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Howard |first1=Jan |title=''Sincerely, Jan Howard'' (liner notes) |journal=[[GRT Records]] |date=1975}}</ref> The album's first and only single to chart was "Seein' Is Believin'", which peaked outside the top 40 of the ''Billboard'' Hot Country Singles list.<ref>{{cite magazine |title="Seein' Is Believin'" chart history |url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/jan-howard/chart-history/csi/ |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> In 1977, she briefly signed with [[Con Brio Records]], where she had three minor hits on the country chart. This included the song, "To Love a Rolling Stone" (1978), which was her final chart appearance.<ref name="whitburn">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2017|publisher=Record Research, Inc|year=2017|isbn=978-0-89820-229-8|pages=171}}</ref> In the late 1970s, she also toured as part of [[Tammy Wynette]]'s roadshow as both a background and lead vocalist.<ref name="Willie Nelson">{{cite web |title=Jan Howard: Country Music Artists: Her Life and Music! |url=https://willienelsonmuseum.com/museum/jan-howard-bio/ |website=Willie Nelson Museum |access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>

In the early 1980s, record producer and friend [[Pete Drake]] asked Howard to be part of a new album series he was producing for Grand Ole Opry members. She agreed to the project and collaborated with Drake on her next studio album.<ref name="liner notes">{{cite journal |last1=Howard |first1=Jan |title=''Stars of the Grand Ole Opry'' (liner notes) |journal=First Generation Records |date=April 1981}}</ref> Titled ''[[Stars of the Grand Ole Opry (Jan Howard album)|Stars of the Grand Ole Opry]]'', the album was released by First Generation Records in April 1981.<ref name="Allmusic">{{cite web |title=''Jan Howard [First Generation]'': Jan Howard: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/jan-howard-first-generation-mw0000252407 |website=[[Allmusic]] |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> It contained re-recorded versions of Howard's hits and several new tracks.<ref name="liner notes"/> Howard continued recording during the decade. Her next studio album was released on [[AVI Records]] in 1983 called ''Tainted Love''.<ref name="Popular Music"/> The album's [[Tainted Love|title track]] was a cover of the hit originally written by [[Ed Cobb]]. Cobb also shared production credits on the album's release.<ref name="Tainted Love">{{cite web |title=Jan Howard - ''Tainted Love'' (1983, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Jan-Howard-Tainted-Love-/release/7156385 |website=[[Discogs]] |date=1983 |access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> In 1985, Howard was part of a joint venture between [[MCA Records|MCA]] and [[Dot Records]], which included several other veteran artists. From the venture, a [[Jan Howard (1985 album)|self-titled studio album]] was released in 1985. Produced by [[Billy Strange]], it was Howard's last studio release.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Howard |first1=Jan |title=''Jan Howard'' [1985] (liner notes) |journal=MCA Records/Dot Records |date=1985}}</ref>

In the 1990s, Howard slowed down her singing career.{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|pp=251}} Howard spoke of her career slow down and her continued passion for singing in her autobiography: "I love to sing and hope that, for a long time to come, God will give me the opportunity to do so. And when he tells me to quit, I hope I have the sense to follow His advice."{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=490}} While working occasionally, she mainly did performances as part of the [[Grand Ole Opry]] cast.{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|pp=251}}<ref name="Opry">{{cite web |title=Jan Howard - Grand Ole Opry |url=https://www.opry.com/artists/jan-howard/ |website=[[Grand Ole Opry]] |access-date=March 21, 2020 |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321023305/https://www.opry.com/artists/jan-howard/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> In the 2000s, Howard was inducted into the Missouri Country Music Hall of Fame and released a boxed set of her recorded material.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jan Howard Discography: Box Sets |url=http://www.janhoward.com/discography.cfm |website=Jan Howard.com |access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> She has since appeared on albums by other artists. In 2007, she recorded a duet with Bill Anderson and [[Vince Gill]] for Anderson's studio release, ''Whisperin' Bluegrass''.<ref>{{cite web |title=''Whisperin' Bluegrass'' - Bill Anderson: Songs, Reviews, Credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/whisperin-bluegrass-mw0000748850 |website=[[Allmusic]] |access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> In 2017, Howard and [[Jessi Colter]] appeared on [[Jeannie Seely]]'s studio album ''[[Written in Song]]'', singing on the track "We're Still Hangin' in There, Ain't We Jessi".<ref>{{cite web |title=Albums Coming in the New Year |url=http://www.cmt.com/news/1775143/11-new-albums-coming-in-the-new-year |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161231063149/http://www.cmt.com/news/1775143/11-new-albums-coming-in-the-new-year/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 31, 2016 |website=[[Country Music Television]] |access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> In 2019, she celebrated her 90th birthday at the Opry, making her the show's oldest living member.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Papadatos |first1=Markos |title=Country queen Jan Howard celebrates 90th birthday |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/music/country-queen-jan-howard-celebrates-90th-birthday/article/545291 |website=Digital Journal |date=March 14, 2019 |access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>

===Style and legacy===
[[File:Jan Backstage at the Opry.jpg|thumb|right|170px|Howard backstage at the Opry, 2017]]
Howard's musical style was rooted in the country and [[Nashville Sound]] genres.<ref name="Allmusic Bio"/>{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|pp=250-51}} Her music has been described as being part of the foundational landscape of country music. [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[Allmusic]] spoke of her singing style in his review of ''The Very Best of Wynn Stewart and Jan Howard'' CD in 2004. "Howard is a strong,, straight-ahead, hardcore country singer, and the sides collected here are excellent, unheralded pure honky-tonk with a Bakersfield tinge."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |title=''The Very Best of Wynn Stewart & Jan Howard'': Wynn Stewart and Jan Howard: Review |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-very-best-of-wynn-stewart-jan-howard-mw0000147845 |website=[[Allmusic]] |access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Robert K. Oermann commented on Howard's "brassy" singing style and noted that her Decca recordings were "downright gutsy", "sassy" and "self-assured."{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=226}} Oermann also spoke on Howard's legacy as an artist: "Jan opened the door for many more Nashville Sound stylists. [[Marion Worth]], [[Margie Bowes]], [[Connie Smith]], [[Jeannie Seely]] and [[Connie Hall]] climbed the charts."{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=229}}

Howard is also remembered for her commercial success. Sandra Brennan of Allmusic called her "one of the hottest female vocalists of the 1960s."<ref name="Allmusic"/> [[Ken Burns]] called her "one of the most popular female country artists of the 1960s and early 1970s."<ref name="PBS"/> Her legacy has also been mentioned in recent years. In 2018, she was ranked among the "100 Greatest Women of Country Music" in a poll by Country Universe.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Coyne |first1=Kevin John |title=100 Greatest Women, #65: Jan Howard |url=http://www.countryuniverse.net/2018/05/27/100-greatest-women-65-jan-howard/ |website=Country Universe |date=May 27, 2018 |access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> In 2005, Howard's single, "Evil on Your Mind", was listed as one of country music's "500 greatest singles" in the book ''Heartaches by the Number''.<ref name="PBS"/> In 1971, she became a member of the [[Grand Ole Opry]] and continued to make public appearances there until 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jan Howard - Grand Ole Opry |url=https://www.opry.com/artists/jan-howard/ |website=[[Grand Ole Opry]] |access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321023305/https://www.opry.com/artists/jan-howard/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==Writing career and other professions==
===1966–1983: Songwriting===
In addition to singing, Howard wrote songs for herself and others. One of her first released compositions was "Crying for Love", which appeared on her 1966 studio album ''[[Jan Howard Sings Evil on Your Mind]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Howard |first1=Jan |title=''Jan Howard Sings Evil on Your Mind'' liner notes (Vinyl insert) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=1966}}</ref> Howard's songs continued to appear on her studio albums over time. Self-penned songs appeared on the studio albums ''[[For God and Country (Jan Howard album)|For God and Country]]'',<ref name="For God Liner Notes">{{cite journal |last1=Howard |first1=Jan |title=''For God and Country'' liner notes (vinyl insert) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=1970}}</ref> ''[[Love Is Like a Spinning Wheel (album)|Love Is Like a Spinning Wheel]]'',<ref name="Spinning Wheel liner notes">{{cite journal |last1=Howard |first1=Jan |title=''Love Is Like a Spinning Wheel'' liner notes (vinyl insert) |journal=[[Decca Records]] |date=1972}}</ref> ''Sincerely, Jan Howard''<ref name="Sincerely">{{cite journal |last1=Howard |first1=Jan |title=''Sincerely, Jan Howard'' (liner notes) |journal=[[GRT Records|GRT]] |date=1975}}</ref> and ''[[Stars of the Grand Ole Opry]]''.<ref name="liner notes"/> Songs she composed were also recorded by other artists. In 1966, she wrote "It's All Over But the Crying", which became a major hit for [[Kitty Wells]].{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=229}} The same year, the song was given among the "Most Frequently Played Tracks" accolade from the [[BMI Awards]]. Howard later called the situation "ironic" because  her husband (Harlan Howard) was better known for songwriting. At the time of the awards dinner, the Howards had separated, but attended the event as a couple.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=283}} 
{{multiple image
 | width1 = 150
 | image1 = Bill Anderson 1970.JPG
 | width2 = 150
 | image2 = Tammy Wynette.JPG
 | footer = As a songwriter, Howard co-wrote songs with [[Bill Anderson (singer)|Bill Anderson]] (left) and [[Tammy Wynette]] (right).
}}

Howard also penned songs with other artists. With Bill Anderson, she wrote "[[I Never Once Stopped Loving You (song)|I Never Once Stopped Loving You]]", which became a major hit for [[Connie Smith]].{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=229}} The pair also co-wrote "Dis-Satisfied", which they made a hit of their own as a duet partnership. Howard's son, Carter, was also given credit on its writing. The song appeared on their studio album ''[[Bill and Jan (Or Jan and Bill)]]''.<ref name="Discogs 2">{{cite web |title=''Bill and Jan (Or Jan and Bill)'' -- Canadian release |url=https://www.discogs.com/Bill-Jan-Bill-Jan-Or-Jan-Bill/release/7781044 |website=[[Discogs]] |date=August 18, 1972 |access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> Howard also self-penned "[[Love Is a Sometimes Thing (song)|Love Is a Sometimes Thing]]," which was recorded and became a major hit for Anderson. She would also release it as a single herself around the same period. These compositions were also awarded BMI Songwriters Awards.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=229}} In 1980, she collaborated with [[Tammy Wynette]] in writing the track "Only the Names Have Been Changed". The song appeared on Wynette's studio album ''[[Only Lonely Sometimes]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tammy Wynette -- ''Only Lonely Sometimes'' (1980, Vinyl) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Tammy-Wynette-Only-Lonely-Sometimes/release/4460023 |website=[[Discogs]] |date=August 18, 1980 |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Her last writing credit is on the track, "My Friend", a song that appeared on Howard's 1983 studio album ''Tainted Love''.<ref name="Tainted Love"/>

===1987–2020: Autobiography and other writing===
For several years, friends told Howard that she should write an [[autobiography]]. In response, she said, "Yeah, it would make a great soap opera."{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=227}} Howard had written an outline for the book, but put it aside for three years before turning to it again.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=283}} She later explained that she chose to continue writing the autobiography because she became suicidal. In 1979, she was visiting a friend in [[Florida]]. "It was a very bad time in my life. I was in Florida and, I didn't know whether I was going to walk into the ocean or not. And I can't swim," Howard said in 2003. Deciding not to end her life, she went back inside the house. She then sat on the floor and wrote a song called "My Story". Howard later threw the song away because it was full of "bitterness". "Once I started again, it was just like rolling back the years," she said in 2003.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=227}}

The year of the book's release, Howard cancelled all her concert engagements to prepare for its completion.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=290}} When officially released in 1987, the autobiography was titled ''Sunshine and Shadow: My Story''. The book was published by Richardson & Steirman, a company based in [[New York, New York|New York City]].{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|pp=251}} ''Sunshine and Shadow'' received mostly positive reviews by critics upon its release. In their July 1987 review, ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' gave the book a positive commentary. Reviewers highlighted stories of Howard's interactions with other country artists and the recounting of her son's suicide. ''Kirkus'' concluded their review by stating, "Sure to be appreciated by die-hard country fans, and by any who seek a tale of victory over despair."<ref>{{cite web |title=Book Reviews: "Sunshine and Shadow" |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/a/jan-howard/sunshine-and-shadow-3/ |website=[[Kirkus Reviews]] |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' gave their review of the release in August 1987. Reviewers of the book praised Howard's personal stories, but disliked the editing style of the book.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nonfiction Book Review: "Sunshine and Shadow" by Jan Howard, Author |url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-931933-48-6 |website=[[Publishers Weekly]] |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>

Also in the late 1980s, Howard explained that she was working on her first fiction short story and a novel.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=229}} In a 2015 interview, Howard explained that she still writes a "little bit of everything" including songs, poems and short stories. Howard also said she had started three fiction novels that had yet to be completed. "I need to put those together, I need to go through them. And I found things in there that I forgot I wrote and I said 'oh, this is pretty good' or 'this is bad'. So right now I'm gonna put those all together and put them in a leather-bound book," Howard said.<ref name="Country Zone">{{cite web |last1=Mecir |first1=Peter |title=Jan Howard: I'll Never Lose The Butterflies |url=http://countryzone.net/en/interviews/499-jan-howard-i-ll-never-lose-the-butterflies |website=Country Zone |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>

[[File:Jan Howard--Real State Card.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Jan Howard's business card from when she was worked as a [[real estate agent]], late 1970s]]
Howard also wrote out her recipes that she used. She featured directions for her recipes on her official website, which were updated on a monthly basis. On her recipe page, website administrators stated, "Each month on this page we’ll be adding a favorite recipe or
two provided by Jan…so keep checking back."<ref>{{cite web |title=Recipes |url=http://www.janhoward.com/recipes.cfm |website=Jan Howard.com |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>

===Other professions and efforts===
In the late 1970s, Howard obtained her [[real estate license]] for a local company in [[Hendersonville, Tennessee]], called Lakeside Realtors. As a realtor, she sold several homes including one to local Nashville musician Jimmy Capps.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=229}} Howard remained a real estate agent for only a short period of time. On her website, she commented that after a while, people would bring "sacks of tapes" for her to listen to rather than be potential clients. "My license is in retirement and will stay there, but I still pay my dues," Howard wrote on her fan page.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jan Howard: Interview questions and answers |url=http://www.janhoward.com/fan_page.cfm |website=Jan Howard.com |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>

In 2002, she appeared with [[Faye Dunaway]] in the film ''Changing Hearts''. Other performers were featured in the cast including [[Rita Coolidge]] and [[Jeannie Seely]].<ref>{{cite web |title=''Changing Hearts'' (2002) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/changing_hearts |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>

After her son was killed in the Vietnam War, Howard worked to support veterans returning from war, including with various organizations in support of the American military [[veteran]]s.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=1}} She worked previously with the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veterans Administration]], [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]], and the [[Vietnam veteran|Vietnam Veteran]] organizations. Howard contributed to a campaign that helped raise funds for the [[Vietnam Veterans Memorial]], which was finished in 1982. From Howard's efforts, she received the "Gold Medal of Merit Award" from the Veterans of Foreign Wars. "I never want to be in the forefront of anything like this, but it’s worth it to bring attention to those who gave so much. If it wasn’t for them, we wouldn’t have the life we enjoy as Americans," Howard commented in 2011.<ref name="Nashville Music Guide">{{cite web |last1=Harman |first1=Ron |title=Veterans Day Holds Special Meaning for Jan Howard |url=https://www.nashvillemusicguide.com/veterans-day-holds-special-meaning-for-jan-howard/ |website=Nashville Music Guide |date=November 18, 2011 |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Since 1982, Howard was involved in veteran-related activities at [[Middle Tennessee State University]], where her son was a former student. In 2017, she made an appearance at the university's veterans' memorial service. She was presented with a "Gold Star Brick" from the school for her work with veterans.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Weiler |first1=Randy |title=Opry member Howard featured as MTSU salutes vets, Gold Star Families |url=https://mtsunews.com/2017-salute-to-vets-game/ |website=[[Middle Tennessee State University]] |date=November 8, 2017 |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>

==Personal life==

===Marriages===
Howard was married four times.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|pp=227-29}} At the time of her first marriage to Mearle Wood, she was only 16 years old.{{sfn|Trott, Walt|2012|p=250}} The couple met when Howard was working at her local drugstore in West Plains, Missouri. He would frequently come by to say hello and have a soda. The two spent more time together, eventually becoming a couple and marrying.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=41-43}} Howard later said that she did not want to marry Wood, but her mother encouraged their courtship. "I felt like I was dressing for a funeral. And in a way, I was. The funeral of my girlhood," she wrote.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=41-43}} Her second marriage to Lowell "Smitty" Smith lasted only two years after discovering that he was a bigamist.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=228}}

In her third marriage to Harlan Howard, Jan's three children legally were adopted by him and took on his last name.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=215}} In the mid-1960s, the couple owned a publishing company in Nashville called "Wilderness Music". Together, they bought an older home, renovated it and turned it into a series of offices for the company.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=230}} Jan later commented that Harlan took control of the Wilderness when they divorced. According to Harlan, the company and its music were his "brainchildren". Upset about the situation, Jan said to her divorce lawyers, "I don't want anything. Just the divorce."{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=291}} Following her divorce, she became closer to her divorce lawyer, Jack Norman. A licensed pilot, Norman took her on plane rides and also spent many nights at her home. The two became romantically involved while Norman was still married.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=305-09}} Their affair carried on into the mid 1970s.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=485}} In 1990, she remarried for a fourth time to Dr. Maurice Acree, Jr.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=228}} Only married for a short period of time,{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=407}} Acree died in 2013, according to an obituary from ''[[The Tennessean]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maurice Acree OBITUARY |url=https://obits.tennessean.com/obituaries/tennessean/obituary.aspx?n=maurice-m-acree&pid=164078081 |website=[[The Tennessean]] |access-date=March 22, 2020 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2024 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

===Children===
From her first marriage, Howard gave birth to three sons: Jimmy, Carter (Corky), and David.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|pp=227-29}} As a young child, Jimmy was hospitalized in critical condition with [[spinal meningitis]]. Within four weeks, he recovered from the illness.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=171-72}} During the Vietnam War in 1968, Jimmy was drafted into the military. Once he received his draft notice, Carter volunteered for the army. "If Jimmy's going, I'm going," he said to Howard.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=321}} After being sent to basic training, the military was supposed to let Jimmy come home, but they refused. Upset about the situation, Howard discussed the situation with her friend and country DJ, [[Ralph Emery]]. Through the assistance of Emery, Howard got in contact with [[Richard Fulton|Congressman Richard Fulton]]. Emery found Fulton at a restaurant at nine o'clock the same night when he contacted him.  Fulton got permission from the military to send Jimmy home for 21 days. In her autobiography, Howard recounted the phone call she received from Jimmy the day he came home, "Mom! What did you do? The Secretary of the Army himself called down here! My sergeant came and got me and said, 'Howard! Go call your mother, then be prepared to work you ass off!'"{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=321}} Howard also recalled Jimmy's nervousness as he prepared for Vietnam. The evening before his departure, he sat at her bedside explaining his nervousness and anxieties. The next evening, he flew out at three o'clock in the morning.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=339}}
{{quote box
 |quote  = The world was black. I prayed for death. The room was filled with people...One by one they filled in. Owen, Hubert, my brothers, Junior, Pete, Dick, and Bob...So many more. Each time I'd open my eyes someone would put a pill in mouth. Merciful sleep. Voices kept coming through. Someone said it would be ten days before they could get the boys home. Then I heard Dr. Goldner say, "she can't live ten days".
 |source =&nbsp;—Howard on the days following her son's death.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=356-57}}
 |width  = 25%
 |align  = left
}}

In October 1968, Jimmy was killed in action.<ref name="Gazette"/> She found out when she saw several friends arrive at the front door of her home. Realizing the reasons for them being there, she began screaming and crying. Howard remembered the days following Jimmy's death in her autobiography, going through the days and weeks by "forcing" herself to keep going. She had trouble eating and sleeping, taking pills on a regular basis to help her through the anxieties and grief. "I was crying when I woke up, and crying when I went to sleep," she wrote in 1987. One morning, Howard made the decision to dispose of all her medicine and continue on with her life. "As I walked into the den and saw the relief on Corky and David's faces, my efforts were worthwhile," she wrote.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=360-61}}

Howard's youngest son, David, began abusing [[substance abuse|drugs]] in the years following Jimmy's death.<ref name="Gazette 2">{{cite news |last1=Edwardsd |first1=Joe |title=Personal Setbacks Make Her Stronger |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1917&dat=19810404&id=AWRGAAAAIBAJ&pg=2414,1548685&hl=en |access-date=March 22, 2020 |publisher=[[Schenectady Gazette]] |date=1981}}</ref> Prior to this, he had been employed at the [[Opryland USA]] theme park, where he appeared as an actor in several shows, including a major role in the cast of the play ''I Hear America Singing''.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=412-13}} Howard then began noticing changes in his behavior, including coming home late at night and having symptoms of [[depression (mood)|depression]]. When she would ask David, he would reply by saying that he was "just tired." She also noticed that he began associating with people who provided David with substances.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=432}} She eventually had him see a [[psychiatrist]] for his personal setbacks, but only found out that he was using the time for other reasons.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=435}} One morning in 1972, Howard found David in his bedroom dead from a self-inflicted gunshot wound. She recalled that the next several days were a "blur". Devastated by her son's suicide, she stayed in bed for days at a time. After many weeks of grieving, Howard cleaned out his room and sold his [[Volkswagen Beetle]]. "When everything was done, I took one last look around, walked out, and closed the door on the past. But it would never be locked," she wrote.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=461-67}}

In the years following David and Jimmy's deaths, Howard's middle son Carter began working with military veterans. He also owned his own business and became a real estate broker in Nashville.<ref name="Gazette 2"/>

===Other personal challenges and death===
The psychological trauma of Howard's childhood affected her as she entered her adult years.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=228}} After giving birth to her third child, she would cry uncontrollably. "There were many times my heart would pound so hard I thought it would pop out of my chest," Howard commented. Howard's sister took her to see a doctor, who explained she was having a "[[nervous breakdown]]". To calm her anxieties, he prescribed Howard a strong pharmaceutical drug she was told to take four times per day.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=86}} In the early 1960s, she was rushed to the hospital after experiencing intense bleeding. Doctors told her, after giving birth to a stillborn baby and a previous operation, Howard had a strong possibility of developing [[cancer]] if she did not have her [[uterus]] removed. Howard underwent surgery at the [[Ronald Reagan UCLA Medical Center|UCLA Medical Center]] in Los Angeles, and within three weeks was back to a normal routine.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=163}}

Her trauma followed her into her marriage with Harlan Howard. While married, her weight dropped below 97 pounds and she would pace their home at night. This prompted Harlan to institutionalize Jan.{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=228}} In her autobiography, she recounted being brought into a hospital room with doctors and nurses. She recalled where she was screaming and shouting until a nurse gave her a shot, which put her "six feet under". A doctor diagnosed her with having [[paroxysmal tachycardia]] and sent her home. He also ordered her to seek [[therapy|counseling]] services from a psychiatrist. According to her psychiatrist, she developed a series of phobias from the traumatic experiences in her childhood.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|pp=186-87}} After moving to Nashville, she continued having depressive episodes. One evening in 1962, she took a handful of sleeping pills and was rushed to the hospital. While at the hospital, her blood pressure dropped significantly low at which she was in critical condition. When she awoke, she recalled seeing [[Maybelle Carter|Mother Maybelle Carter]] feeding her. "Little by little I felt stronger and knew, thank God, that I was going to live," she wrote.{{sfn|Howard, Jan|1987|p=227}}

Years later, Howard reflected on her life experiences: "One thing I want to make clear is that I'm not a martyr. I can't stand self-pity. I don't deserve and don't want any kind of pity...There are a lot of people who have gone through worse things than I have."{{sfn|Oermann, Robert K.|Bufwack, Mary A.|2003|p=229}}

Howard died on March 28, 2020, fifteen days after her 91st birthday, in [[Gallatin, Tennessee]]. The cause of death was [[pneumonia]].<ref name="NY Times"/> "We were all so lucky so many nights to hear her voice on stage and to catch up with her backstage. We’re all better for having had her in our lives," said Dan Rogers, Vice President of the Grand Ole Opry.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Paulson |first1=Dave |title=Jan Howard, Opry member and country star, dies at 91 |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2020/03/28/jan-howard-opry-member-and-country-star-dies-91/2934701001/ |website=[[The Tennessean]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> She is buried at [[Spring Hill Cemetery (Nashville, Tennessee)|Spring Hill Cemetery]], in Nashville.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ms. Jan Howard: Obituary |url=https://www.springhillfh.com/obituaries/Jan-Howard-3/#!/Obituary |website=Spring Hill |access-date=March 29, 2021}}</ref>

